{
  "civicsStory": [
    {
      "chapterId": 1,
      "translations": {
        "en": {
          "title": "Blueprint for Freedom: The Birth of the Constitution",
          "introduction": "Before the United States became a nation, the great Founding Fathers drew up the most important 'blueprint.' Without this Constitution, today's America would not exist."
        }
      },
      "sections": [
        {
          "content_en": [
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": "Once upon a time, there were people who dreamed of freedom and justice. As they established a new nation, they declared: \"We shall live as a "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Republic"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ", under the principles of a "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Constitution-based federal republic"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ", and create a nation of "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Representative democracy"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": " where people govern themselves through representatives!\" (Q.1). The supreme law supporting their promise was the "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Constitution"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": " (Q.2). This "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Constitution"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": " was not just words, but the framework and promise of the nation. It contained provisions to "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "form the government"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "define powers of government"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "define the parts of government"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ", and most importantly, "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "protect the rights of the people"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": " (Q.3). The Constitution begins with these words: \"We the People.\" Here, \"We the People\" symbolizes "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Self-government"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Popular sovereignty"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Consent of the governed"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "People should govern themselves"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ", and "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Social contract"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": " (Q.4). But the Constitution was not a document written once and forgotten. To adapt to changing times, "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Amendments"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": " were created through "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "The amendment process"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": " (Q.5). The most famous amendments are the "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Bill of Rights"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ". These provisions protect "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "basic rights of Americans"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": " and "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "basic rights of people living in the United States"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": " (Q.6). So far, a total of "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "27"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": " amendments have been added to the Constitution (Q.7). However, everything started with one document: the "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Declaration of Independence"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ". That document "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "announced our independence from Great Britain"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ", stated that "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "all men are created equal"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ", and defined "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "inalienable rights"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": " and "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "individual freedom"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": " (Q.8, Q.9). Together, that document and the Constitution conveyed core values of "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Equality"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Liberty"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Social contract"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Natural rights"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Limited government"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ", and "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Self-government"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": " (Q.10). And the words that touched people's hearts deeply, \"Life, Liberty, and the pursuit of Happiness,\" came from the "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Declaration of Independence"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": " (Q.11). Built upon these ideas, America's economy follows the principles of "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Capitalist economy"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": " and "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Free market economy"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": " (Q.12). However, even a free country needed order. Thus emerged the concept of "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Rule of law"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ". This means "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Everyone must obey the law"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Leaders must obey the law"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Government must obey the law"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ", and "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "No one is above the law"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": " (Q.13). In creating this Constitution, "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Declaration of Independence"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Articles of Confederation"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Federalist Papers"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Virginia Declaration of Rights"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Fundamental Orders of Connecticut"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Mayflower Compact"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ", and "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Iroquois Great Law of Peace"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": " had great influence (Q.14). Finally, to prevent power from concentrating in one place, America created three branches. This is the principle of "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Separation of powers"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": " and "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "Checks and balances"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": ", designed to ensure that "
            },
            {
              "type": "answer",
              "text": "one part of the government does not become too powerful"
            },
            {
              "type": "normal",
              "text": " (Q.15)."
            }
          ],
